<dl id="n10066e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10066e">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10066e"> 66(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Iris Mercury Hermes <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10066e"><li>FW 454.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n10066e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n10066e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10066e">MS BL 47482b-55</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:111 <a name="qA3d" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qA3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/q/qa3d.htm#n10066e">Draft: III&sect;2A.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">On se demande comment il se fait que les nombreux mythologistes du Comit&eacute; du concours de 1875, n&apos;ont point song&eacute; &agrave; <mark>Iris</mark>, la prompte messag&egrave;re des dieux, dont parle le po&egrave;te latin&hellip;. &hellip; Tel &eacute;tait le sujet mythologique tout trouv&eacute; qui permettait une fois pour toutes de laisser de c&ocirc;t&eacute; le dieu-messager <mark>Mercure</mark> &agrave; la Banque, o&ugrave; il est vraiment &agrave; sa place. <font color="green">[We wonder why none of the many mythologists at the Contest Committee in 1875 thought of Iris, the swift messenger of the gods who is spoken of by the Latin poet [&hellip;]</font>. This obvious mythological choice would have allowed us once and for all to relegate the god-messenger Mercury to the Bank, where he belongs by rights.] <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 285</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also: <a name="n10137f" href="n10all.htm#n10137f">N10 (VI.B.16):137(f)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
